V{{independent sources|date=October 2013}}\u000a{{Infobox philosopher\u000a| image            = \u000a| region           = \u000a| era              = [[20th-century philosophy]]\u000a| color            = #B0C4DE\u000a| name             = Rada Ivekovic \u000a| birth_date       = 1945\u000a| birth_place      = [[Zagreb]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]\u000a| death_date       = \u000a| school_tradition = [[Buddhist philosophy]], [[feminist philosophy]]\u000a| main_interests   = [[Political philosophy]], feminist philosophy\u000a| influences       = \u000a| influenced       = \u000a| notable_ideas    = "Le partage de la raison"\u000a}}\u000a'''Rada Ivekovi\u0107''' (born 1945 in [[Zagreb]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]) is a Croatian professor, [[Philosophy|philosopher]], [[Indology|Indologist]], and writer.\u000a\u000a== Research ==\u000aIvekovic\u2019s research interests include [[comparative philosophy]] ([[Asian philosophy]], particularly [[Indian philosophy|Indian]], and [[Western philosophy|Western]]), [[feminist theory]] and [[feminist philosophy]] as well as [[political philosophy]].{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\u000a\u000aIn particular, the following aspects have been of intellectual inspiration for Ivekovic\u2019s work:  [[contemporary European philosophy]], [[postmodern philosophy]], [[Orientalism]] in (Western) philosophy, the feminine in philosophy, issues of [[nation]], [[Sovereign state|state]] und [[citizenship]], problems of [[nationalism]], of [[violence]] and [[war]], European [[Cultural identity|identity]] issues, and [[democracy]].{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\u000a\u000aIvekovic\u2019s other interests include: [[literary theory]] and [[literary criticism]], [[religion]] and [[mythology]], [[gender studies]] and [[women writers]], [[anthropology]], and  [[contemporary French philosophy]] in particular.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\u000a\u000a== Political positioning ==\u000aIvekovic holds that the inequality of the sexes (Inégalité des sexes) and other [[Alterity|alterities]], [[social equality|inequalities]], [[Outcast (person)|exclusion]]s, subordinating [[Inclusion (value and practice)|inclusion]]s (e.g. through discrimination by  [[gender]], [[Nation|national citizenship]], [[ethnicity]], [[colonization]]) leads to a fatal partitioning of reason ("Le partage de la raison"). On the war events on the territory of Yugoslavia she takes an explicitly anti-patriarchal, anti-racist and non-nationalist stance.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\u000a\u000aIn 1997 Ivekovic published a study on gender/sex in philosophy, taking issue with [[Jean-François Lyotard]].\u000a\u000a== Career ==\u000aIvekovi\u0107 grew up mostly in [[Zagreb]] and [[Belgrade]], living in Zagreb, from 1963 until leaving Croatia for exile in 1991-1992 in a self-described "protest against nationalism."\u000a\u000aAt [[Zagreb University]], she studied Indology, Philosophy and English Studies (1969) and from 1970 to 1973, [[Buddhist philosophy]] at [[Delhi University]] where she received her PhD in 1972.\u000a\u000aFrom 1975 to 1991-1992, Ivekovi\u0107 was a Lecturer in the History of Asian Philosophy and Comparative Philosophy at Zagreb University. From 1998-2003 she was a professor at Paris VIII. Since 2003 Professor in the Department of Sociology at [[University Jean Monnet - St.Etienne]] and after 2004, the Program Director at [[Collège international de philosophie (Paris)]].\u000a\u000a== Selected works in English ==\u000a*1984: She and Slavenka Drakuli\u0107-Illi\u0107 contributed the piece "Neofeminism, and its six mortal sins" to the 1984 anthology ''[[Sisterhood Is Global: The International Women's Movement Anthology]]'', edited by [[Robin Morgan]].<ref name="global">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.vsc.edu/lscfind/Record/154795/TOC#tabnav |title=Table of Contents: Sisterhood is global : |publisher=Catalog.vsc.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-10-15}}</ref>\u000a*2004: "COMMENTARY - The Veil in France: Secularism, Nation, Women". ''Economic and Political Weekly''. Vol. 39, 11, 1117-1119.\u000a*2005: "Borders and Partitions: Exception as Space and Time" (Abstract for the conference ''Polemos, Stasis ... War, Civil War'', 24\u201327 June 2005, [[National Chiao Tung University]], Taiwan: Center for Humanities and Social Theory). [http://chst.nctu.edu.tw/war/abstract_Rada.htm]\u000a*2005: "The Fiction of Gender Constructing the Fiction of Nation: On How Fictions Are Normative, and Norms Produce Exceptions". ''Anthropological Yearbook of European Cultures 2005'' (Gender and Nation in South Eastern Europe), 19-38.\u000a\u000a== Sources ==\u000a{{no footnotes|date=August 2013}}\u000a{{Reflist}}\u000a*[http://chst.nctu.edu.tw/war/Rada_CV.htm Most comprehensive CV, until 2004, in English]\u000a*[http://www-gewi.uni-graz.at/nabl/intercity/ivekovic.htm Short portrait in German with photo,  1997]\u000a\u000a==Further reading==\u000a*Grebowicz, Margret. ''Gender after Lyotard''. Albany: State University of New York Press, 2007.\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Ivekovic, Rada}}\u000a[[Category:1945 births]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:Buddhist feminists]]\u000a[[Category:Buddhist philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Buddhist writers]]\u000a[[Category:Croatian Buddhists]]\u000a[[Category:Croatian feminists]]\u000a[[Category:Croatian philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Croatian women writers]]\u000a[[Category:Feminist philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Indologists]]\u000a[[Category:People from Zagreb]]\u000a[[Category:Political philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Postmodern feminists]]\u000a[[Category:University of Belgrade Faculty of Philosophy alumni]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Croatian women philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century women writers]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century women writers]]\u000a[[Category:Women orientalists]]
